# aws-kinesis Best Practices

## Code Organization and Structure

Organize your Kinesis-related code into clear modules to enhance maintainability and readability. Use a dedicated directory for Kinesis producers and consumers.

### Directory Structure
```plaintext
/my-app
├── kinesis
│   ├── producers
│   │   └── kinesisProducer.js
│   ├── consumers
│   │   └── kinesisConsumer.js
│   └── utils
│       └── kinesisUtils.js
└── ...
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use Kinesis Producer Library (KPL) for High Throughput

When producing records, always use the Kinesis Producer Library (KPL) to optimize throughput and reduce latency.

❌ BAD: Using `PutRecord` for individual records.
```javascript
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const kinesis = new AWS.Kinesis();

async function sendSingleRecord(data) {
    await kinesis.putRecord({
        StreamName: 'my-stream',
        Data: JSON.stringify(data),
        PartitionKey: 'partitionKey'
    }).promise();
}
```

✅ GOOD: Using KPL for batching records.
```javascript
const { KinesisProducer } = require('aws-kinesis-producer');

const producer = new KinesisProducer({ streamName: 'my-stream' });

async function sendRecords(records) {
    await producer.send(records.map(data => ({
        Data: JSON.stringify(data),
        PartitionKey: 'partitionKey'
    })));
}
```

### Implement Exponential Backoff for Retries

Always implement retry logic with exponential backoff to handle `ProvisionedThroughputExceededException`.

❌ BAD: Ignoring retry logic.
```javascript
async function sendRecord(data) {
    await kinesis.putRecord({ /* ... */ }).promise();
}
```

✅ GOOD: Implementing exponential backoff.
```javascript
async function sendRecordWithRetry(data, retries = 5) {
    for (let i = 0; i < retries; i++) {
        try {
            await kinesis.putRecord({ /* ... */ }).promise();
            return; // Success
        } catch (error) {
            if (error.code === 'ProvisionedThroughputExceededException') {
                const backoffTime = Math.pow(2, i) * 100; // Exponential backoff
                await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, backoffTime));
            } else {
                throw error; // Other errors
            }
        }
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Use Enhanced Fan-Out for Lambda Consumers

When using Lambda as a consumer, always utilize Enhanced Fan-Out (EFO) to achieve lower latencies.

❌ BAD: Using standard polling for Lambda.
```javascript
exports.handler = async (event) => {
    // Process records
};
```

✅ GOOD: Using Enhanced Fan-Out.
```javascript
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const kinesis = new AWS.Kinesis();

exports.handler = async (event) => {
    const records = event.Records.map(record => {
        return Buffer.from(record.kinesis.data, 'base64').toString('utf-8');
    });
    // Process records
};
```

### Monitor Iterator Age and Shard Metrics

Regularly monitor `IteratorAgeMilliseconds` and shard-level metrics to detect processing delays.

✅ GOOD: Setting up CloudWatch alarms.
```javascript
const cloudwatch = new AWS.CloudWatch();

cloudwatch.putMetricAlarm({
    AlarmName: 'HighIteratorAge',
    MetricName: 'IteratorAgeMilliseconds',
    Namespace: 'AWS/Kinesis',
    Statistic: 'Average',
    Period: 60,
    EvaluationPeriods: 1,
    Threshold: 10000, // 10 seconds
    ComparisonOperator: 'GreaterThanThreshold',
    AlarmActions: ['arn:aws:sns:region:account-id:alert'],
    Dimensions: [{ Name: 'StreamName', Value: 'my-stream' }]
}).promise();
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Hot Shards

Select high-cardinality partition keys to distribute load evenly across shards and avoid hot shards.

❌ BAD: Using a single partition key for all records.
```javascript
const partitionKey = 'commonKey'; // Hot shard
```

✅ GOOD: Using dynamic partition keys.
```javascript
const partitionKey = generateDynamicKey(data); // High-cardinality key
```

### Handle Partial Failures

Always account for partial failures in non-atomic operations and enforce idempotency.

❌ BAD: Processing records without idempotency.
```javascript
async function processRecord(data) {
    // Process data
}
```

✅ GOOD: Implementing idempotency.
```javascript
const processedIds = new Set();

async function processRecord(data) {
    if (!processedIds.has(data.id)) {
        // Process data
        processedIds.add(data.id);
    }
}
```

## Testing Approaches

### Mock Kinesis for Unit Tests

Use mocking libraries to simulate Kinesis interactions in unit tests, ensuring that tests are fast and reliable.

✅ GOOD: Mocking Kinesis with Jest.
```javascript
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
jest.mock('aws-sdk');

const kinesis = new AWS.Kinesis();

test('should send record', async () => {
    kinesis.putRecord.mockReturnValueOnce({ promise: jest.fn().mockResolvedValue({}) });
    
    await sendRecordWithRetry({ id: '1' });
    
    expect(kinesis.putRecord).toHaveBeenCalled();
});
```

### Integration Testing with LocalStack

For integration tests, use LocalStack to simulate AWS services locally.

✅ GOOD: Running LocalStack for integration tests.
```bash
# Start LocalStack
localstack start

# Run your integration tests against LocalStack
```

## Conclusion

Following these best practices will ensure that your aws-kinesis implementations are efficient, maintainable, and resilient. Always prioritize performance, monitoring, and proper error handling to create robust streaming applications.